## Risk Assessment at the Capstone Stage — What Has Changed

Day 88 produced the compliance mapping — four-layer traceability from HIPAA requirement through NIST control through SSP implementation through evidence chain, with honest ⚠️ markers for the two gaps currently in progress. The compliance mapping revealed the program's coverage structure. Day 89 is about the risk picture that the program was built to address — and how that picture has evolved over eight months of authorized operation and continuous monitoring.

I want to be direct about the difference between this capstone risk assessment and the initial risk assessment conducted in Days 38-40. The Day 38 risk register was built prospectively — identifying threats before the system was fully operational, estimating likelihoods and impacts based on the threat landscape at categorization time, and establishing the risk baseline that the authorization was built on.

The Day 89 risk assessment is built retrospectively and currently — it incorporates eight months of operational evidence. The continuous monitoring program has produced real findings that either validate or update the initial risk ratings. The HC3 threat intelligence briefing from Q1 monitoring changed the likelihood rating for one risk category. The M-002, A-7, and M-004 findings all revealed process-layer risks that the technical control inventory did not fully capture at initial assessment. The AU-12 self-assessment finding revealed an implementation gap in a control that was assessed as compliant.

The capstone risk summary should reflect this evolved picture — not a retrospective recreation of the initial assessment, but the current risk posture as it actually exists after eight months of operation, monitoring, and mitigation.

