## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified risk assessment maturity today is the distinction between a point-in-time risk assessment and a risk register that reflects operational learning.

A point-in-time risk assessment documents the risk picture at a specific moment — the initial categorization, the pre-authorization assessment, the re-authorization assessment. These are high-rigor, structured assessments that produce formal documentation. They are necessary but inherently backward-looking — they capture the risk picture at the moment of assessment.

A risk register that reflects operational learning incorporates the lessons that ongoing monitoring produces: a control that was assessed as effective but degraded over time, a threat actor whose capabilities increased based on threat intelligence, a vulnerability that was rated Low at assessment but was exploited in a comparable organization and warrants re-evaluation. The risk register is not a snapshot — it is a living document that the continuous monitoring program keeps current.

The eight months of OpenMRS operation have produced exactly this kind of operational learning. The risk register at the capstone stage is more accurate than the risk register at authorization — not because the initial assessment was wrong, but because operational experience produces information that prospective risk assessment cannot generate.

