## What the Risk Register Reveals — Integrated View

Two patterns emerge from looking at the complete current-state risk register that would not be visible from individual daily entries:

**Pattern 1 — The threat environment has elevated in two specific areas.** RS-001 (credential theft) and RS-004 (ransomware) both increased from Moderate to High based on the HC3 Q1 briefing. These two risks share a threat vector — phishing campaigns targeting healthcare EHR credential theft as a ransomware precursor. The single most impactful second-year security improvement for both risks is the phishing simulation program: it converts the security awareness training from a documentation exercise into a measured behavioral intervention targeted at exactly the attack vector the threat intelligence identifies as elevated.

**Pattern 2 — The AU-12 denied-access logging gap affects multiple risks.** The Day 79 self-assessment finding that denied access events are not logged affects both RS-001 (inability to detect systematic credential probing) and RS-005 (inability to detect insider probing of records outside role scope). One technical remediation — fixing the OpenMRS audit log's denied-access event capture — improves the detection capability for two of the program's Moderate residual risks simultaneously. This is the type of compound benefit that the integrated risk register reveals.

Both patterns point to the same two second-year priorities: the phishing simulation program (addresses elevated threat landscape) and the AU-12 remediation (addresses detection capability across multiple risk scenarios). Both are currently in the POA&M or pending POA&M entry. Neither is new — they were identified through the continuous monitoring program. What the capstone risk register does is show why they are the right priorities.

